Individuals who have the ambition and potential to start their own firm but have not yet made any substantial moves in that direction are considered nascent entrepreneurs. Nascent intrapreneurs are similar in that they have the capacity and desire to launch a new endeavor inside an existing business, but have yet to take any meaningful moves in that direction. Individuals who have the capability and desire to start their own company but have not yet recognized an opportunity or made any meaningful steps toward doing so are considered latent entrepreneurs. All three kinds of entrepreneurs want to establish their own firm or endeavor, but they are at various phases of the process. 